history.text: Hi!
Lmao Gatsby is ridiculous right?
Definitely. Parties every night, just to try to impress a girl.
it reminds me of Darcy from Pride and Prejudice in the amount of straight guy struggling to get the girl lol
It is excessive. She's already married to a different rich guy and has moved on.
it doesn't seem like the movie itself was well received. I know the book is a classic
Yes, I agree that putting aside your literary agendas is the best way to enjoy it.
I vaguely remember the movie but all I remember was the cool costumes
There were some crazy costumes. I enjoyed the spectacle of the whole thing--everything was so flashy.
also "splashy trashy opera" is so accurate I'm dying
So accurate.
I like that the movie is framed with Nick's time in rehab, telling the story of Gatsby.
yeah exactly! I liked that it was told from outside point of view because if it were from Gatsby it would be like "why doesn't she like my epic parties?????"" lmao
Apparently the green light is an important example of symbolism
Gatsby's version would be boring. He would spend all of the time describing how great the parties are and how expensive everything is.
lmao he really would. "I wore this fancy coat I got in paris and had fireworks..." seeing it from Nick's point of view was great
also added a lot of suspense because you don't know what's gonna happen
It's interesting that he describes Gatsby as hopeful, when he always just seemed sad to me.

I guess he's hopeful in the wrong way? Like you can be hopeful if you have a reasonable chance, but Gatsby is just hoping for something that never is gonna happen, which yeah I agree makes him pretty sad
damn this movie plot is a lot more complicated that I thought!!
Yes, I was just trying to unravel the rest. Daisy is trying too hard to be on both sides of the issue.
yeah it seems like she genuinly might actually like Gatsby but she's stuck with Tom
She didn't wait for Gatsby to get rich and she settled for Tom, and now she has to stick with her choice.
But Myrtle's death was shocking.
